        <name>37.1.1.9 Morse Code</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
&lt;li&gt; How many different signals consisting of \({@symb@}\) symbols can be sent using the dot and dash of Morse code? [[input:ans1]][[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt; How many can be sent if {@symb@} symbols &lt;span&gt;&lt;em&gt;or less&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt; can be sent? [[input:ans2]][[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]
&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;h4 class="HELM_solution"&gt;Solution&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;Clearly, the order of the symbols is important. We can choose each symbol in two ways, either a dot or a dash. The number of distinct signals is
        &lt;br&gt;\(\qquad 2\times \cdots \times 2= 2^{@symb@}={@ta1@}\).&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;If {@symb@} &lt;span&gt;&lt;em&gt;or less&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt; symbols may be used, the total number of signals may be calculated as follows:
        &lt;br&gt;Using one symbol \(2^1 = 2\) ways
        &lt;br&gt; Using two symbols:\(2\times 2= 2^2=4\) ways
        &lt;br&gt;...&lt;br&gt;Using {@symb@} symbols:\(2^{@symb@}={@ta1@}\) ways
        &lt;br&gt;The total number of signals which may be sent is: \[\sum_{n=1}^{@symb@} 2^n = 2^1 + 2^2 + \cdots + 2^{@symb@} = {@ta2@}.\]&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</generalfeedback>
